Ill begin by loading the hexagons pre-computed hexagons of the city using the h3 package. For the further analyses I will use a spatial resolution of \(8\):

setwd('/home/link92/Downloads/R session/project')

# load the hexagons @ resolution 8
tv_hexagons <- st_read('rel_frequencies_res8/basemap_8.shp')
## Reading layer `basemap_8' from data source 
##   `/home/link92/Downloads/R session/project/rel_frequencies_res8/basemap_8.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 76 features and 2 fields
## Geometry type: POLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: 45.61278 ymin: 12.16901 xmax: 45.7094 ymax: 12.28744
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
plot(st_geometry(tv_hexagons))

# create contiguity-based neighbors starting from the hexagons
contnb_q <- poly2nb(tv_hexagons, queen=T)
plot(st_geometry(tv_hexagons), border='blue')

# create row-standardized weight matrix
W <- nb2listw(contnb_q, style='W')

The data has been divided into train and test based on the year:

  • the train set (df_train) includes data from 2005 to 2017
  • the test set (df_test) includes data from 2018 to 2022
df_train <- read.csv(file='rel_frequencies_res8/hexagon_dataframe_rel_freq_train_res8.csv')
df_test <- read.csv(file='rel_frequencies_res8/hexagon_dataframe_rel_freq_test_res8.csv')

Since the hexagons in df_train and df_test do not fully cover the basemap (i.e.some hexagons have no accidents), Ill reconstruct both dataframes based on the col_hex_id and fill in any empty hexagons with zeros. This will ensure that the weight matrix remains consistent.

new_df_train <- data.frame(matrix(0, nrow=length(W$weights), ncol=length(colnames(df_train))))
colnames(new_df_train) <- colnames(df_train)

new_df_test <- data.frame(matrix(0, nrow=length(W$weights), ncol=length(colnames(df_test))))
colnames(new_df_test) <- colnames(df_test)

# loop hexagons and add the corresponding rows to the new_df
for (i in seq(1, length(tv_hexagons$col_hex_8))){
  curr_hex <- tv_hexagons$col_hex_8[i]
  
  if (curr_hex %in% df_train$col_hex_8){
    row_to_ins <- df_train[df_train$col_hex_8 == curr_hex, ]
    new_df_train[i, ] <- row_to_ins
  }
  
  if (curr_hex %in% df_test$col_hex_8){
    row_to_ins <- df_test[df_test$col_hex_8 == curr_hex, ]
    new_df_test[i, ] <- row_to_ins
  }
}


# remove also the hexagon_id information, and some of the variables that do not
# make any sense to include in order to predict the y or that cause trouble while training the following models

new_df_train <- subset(new_df_train, select=-c(col_hex_8, Feriti, Morti, elettrici, ghiacciato, Strada.pavimentata.dissestata, Altra.strada, Altro.tempo, Altra.pavimentazione))
new_df_test <- subset(new_df_test, select=-c(col_hex_8, Feriti, Morti, elettrici, ghiacciato, Strada.pavimentata.dissestata, Altra.strada, Altro.tempo, Altra.pavimentazione))

Some of the coefficient were not computed, this is because the correspondent variables are Aliases (i.e., correlated to one another). As a solution, Ill use a stepwise method in order to keep the relevant variables only, while also removing the collinear ones.

# forward + backward
stp <- ols_step_both_p(OLSmodel)

According to the stepwise method, the variables listed below are the most significant in determining the number of accidents:

stp$predictors

All the variables, except for bus and In.cubetti.di.porfido are significant in predicting the number of accidents In particular, it is possible to note that:

  • for each unit increase in the variables Nebbia and Rettilineo, there is a decrease of \(988\) and \(106\) in the number of accidents, respectively. However, it is counterintuitive that an increase in the accidents under fog conditions would lead to a decrease in the number of predicted accidents.

  • for each unit increase in the variables Intersezione, Contro.veicoli.fermi, bici and Investimento, there is an increase in the number of predicted accidents. This makes sense as intersections are typically unregulated (i.e.no traffic lights) and high traffic conditions are known to lead to a higher likelihood of accidents. For what concerns the involvement of bikes and pedestrians, it could be that higher proportions of their involvement is the result of a general overcrowding (of both vehicles and people) in those areas.

As you can see, apart from bus, and In.cubetti.di.porfido all the chosen variables are significant in predicting the number of accidents. In particular we notice that:

Does it make any sense to account for spatial information while fitting a model?

OLSmodel <- lm(y ~ bici + Intersezione + In.cubetti.di.porfido + Nebbia + Traffico.Intenso +
                   Contro.veicoli.fermi + Rettilineo + Investimento + bus, data=new_df_train)

OLSlmtests <- lm.LMtests(OLSmodel, listw=W, test=c("LMerr", "LMlag", "RLMerr", "RLMlag"))
summary(OLSlmtests)

According to the results of the LM diagnostics, it seems that there is no significant spatial dependence. As a result, a linear model is not any statistically different from a Spatial Error Model or a Spatial Lag Model. We can still try to fit these models, but I expect the parameter Rho to be non significant:

SDM <- lagsarlm(y ~ Intersezione + In.cubetti.di.porfido + Nebbia + Traffico.Intenso +
                   Contro.veicoli.fermi + Rettilineo + Investimento + bus, data=new_df_train,
                   listw=W, type='mixed')

Now Ill fit a Decision Tree:

full_tr <- tree(y ~ ., data=new_df_train)

plot(full_tr)
text(full_tr, pretty=0)

It is important to stress on the fact that the data was re-processed into relative frequencies, which means that each group of variables is interconnected. For example, the variable bici represents the proportion of accidents that involved bikes relatively to all the accidents that involved the other vehicles.

According to the resulting decision tree:

  • On the left branch: if the proportion of Contro.veicoli.fermi is \(> 0.003\), it then looks at the proportion of accidents that occurred at Incrocio. If that is \(> 0.503\) it estimates \(12.54\) accidents for that area. If not, it estimates \(61.50\) accidents.

  • On the right branch: if the proportion of Contro.veicoli.fermi is \(>0.003\), it then looks at the proportion of accidents that involved \(bici\). If this is \(> 0.193\), it further checks the media.veicoli.coinvolti. If that is \(> 1.957\), the estimated number of accidents for that area i 55.60, otherwise its \(132.20\). If the proportion of accidents that involved bici is \(< 0.193\) instead, it looks for the proportions of accidents with \(luce\), if that proportion is \(>0.795\), the estimated number of accidents is \(188.20\), otherwise is \(371.60\).

Now Ill check if it is possible to prune the tree:

cv_tree <- cv.tree(full_tr, K=nrow(new_df_train)-1)

plot(cv_tree, type='b')

best_cut <- data.frame(cv_tree$size, cv_tree$dev)

best_cut <- best_cut[order(cv_tree$dev), ][1, 1]

We can prune it at \(4\) leaves:

pruned_t <- prune.tree(full_tr, best=best_cut)
plot(pruned_t)
text(pruned_t, pretty=0)

According to the pruned version of the tree, we can get similar results without accounting for media.veicoli.coinvolti and the proportions of accidents in Incrocio. So:

  • on the left branch: if the proportions of accidents of type Contro.veicoli.fermi is \(>0.003\), the estimated number of accidents is \(18.79\).
  • on the right branch: if the proportions of accidents of type Contro.veicoli.fermi is \(>0.003\), the model further looks for the proportion of accidents that involved bici, if that is \(> 0.193\), the estimated number of accidents is \(81.13\), otherwise the model also check for the proportion of accidents that were in conditions of luce, if those are \(>0.795\), the estimated number of accidents is \(188.20\), otherwise is \(371.60\).

If the model performs practically good, we can say that areas with a really small number of proportions of accidents Contro.veicoli.fermi are typically associated with a higher number of accidents overall. Moreover, in this case, if the proportions of involved bikes (bici) is \(<0.193\), then, the number of accidents is going to be even higher (otherwise \(188.20\)). In this case, also the proportions of accidents in light conditions (luce) is taken into account, if the proportions of accidents with luce is \(<0.79\), the number of accidents is going to be higher: \(371.60\).

Let us see if the models hold while predicting new/unseen observations:

lin_preds <- predict(OLSmodel, newdata=new_df_test)
lin_preds <- ifelse(lin_preds < 0, 0, lin_preds)

full_preds <- predict(full_tr, newdata=new_df_test)

pruned_preds <- predict(pruned_t, newdata=new_df_test)

#RMSE Full Tree
r_full <- sqrt(sum((full_preds - new_df_test$y)^2) / length(new_df_test$y))

# RMSE Pruned Tree
r_pruned <- sqrt(sum((pruned_preds - new_df_test$y)^2) / length(new_df_test$y))

# RMSE Linear Model
r_lin <- sqrt(sum((lin_preds - new_df_test$y)^2) / length(new_df_test$y))

barplot(names=c('Linear', 'Full tree', 'Pruned tree'), c(r_lin, r_full, r_pruned),
        main="Models' performance (lower is better)", ylab='RMSE', ylim=c(0, r_lin))

paste0(c('Linear model', r_lin), sep=':')
## [1] "Linear model:"     "159.412435758482:"
paste0(c('Full Tree', r_full), sep=':')
## [1] "Full Tree:"        "102.459875971272:"
paste0(c('Pruned Tree', r_pruned), sep=':')
## [1] "Pruned Tree:"      "100.550268562651:"

With respect to a linear model, both the full and the pruned trees are definitely better. The pruned one is, as expected, pretty much the same as the full one. On average, the pruned tree estimates the number of accidents with an error of 100 per area.

Now Ill try to fit also a Random Forest model. First Ill fit multiple Random Forests, so to understand what is the best number of (randomly sampled) variables to account for:

set.seed(42)
res <- matrix(nrow=ncol(new_df_train) - 1, ncol=1)
m <- 1:(ncol(new_df_train) - 1)

for (i in m){
  rf = randomForest(y ~ ., data=new_df_train, mtry=i, K=nrow(new_df_train)-1, OOB_score=F)
  res[i, 1] <- mean(rf$mse)
}

res <- data.frame(CV=res[, 1])

plot(x=seq(1, nrow(res)), y=res$CV, type='l', col='red', xlab='mtry', ylab='error', main='LOOCV error according to the number of sampled variables')

The number of variables that grants a lower error is \(35\), but \(22\) grants an equivalently low error:

set.seed(42)
rf <- randomForest(y ~ ., localImp=T, data=new_df_train, mtry=22)

Random Forest is not very friendly with interpretability, nonetheless, Ill squeeze information out as much as it is possible.

First we look at the distribution of minimal depth. This plot allows us to see at - as the name says - the distribution of minimal depth among the trees. The vertical bar indicates the mean of the distribution, the scale of X goes from zero to the maximum number of trees in which the variable was used for splitting. This plot allows us to see which variables were split the closest to the root of each tree. When this is low, it means that a lot of variables are divided into groups based on that variable (i.e., that variable is important in explaining the number of accidents):

plot_min_depth_distribution(rf, mean_sample='relevant_trees')

We can see that most of the times In.cubetti.di.porfido is chosen as root node. This is quite significant, since the city of Treviso has that kind of pavement only in the city center. Being chosen as a root node it means that it is the best splitting variable, which means that areas with that pavement are very different from areas without that kind of pavement. Despite of that, we also notice that this variable is not picked in lots of trees. We notice, instead, that Intersezione not only is chosen as root nodes in most of the trees, but also that it is picked a lot in the trees, in general. Also the variables Bici and Investimento and Traffico.Intenso seem to play a relevant role as nodes at height \(=1\).

Half of the times Rotatoria is not used to determine the number of accidents, so, it seems that knowing the proportions of Incrocio and Intersezione is more relevant.

Now Ill look into the Multi-way importance plot. It shows the relation between three relevant measures:

  • mean depth of first split on the variable
  • number of trees in which the root is split on the variable
  • total number of nodes in the forest that split on that variable

Looking at this plot from top-left to bottom-right we can understand the most important variables:

The higher a variable it is, the most times it is chosen as a root node; the most it is on the left, the lower it is in the tree.

importance_frame <- measure_importance(rf)

plot_multi_way_importance(importance_frame, size_measure='no_of_nodes')

Here it appears quite clear that Contro.veicoli.fermi and Intersezione are relevant variables since these are picked, on average, at low depths of the trees, often also as roots. Also bici, Investimento and Traffico.Intenso play their important role. In general, all the variables marked in blue seem to be relevant for the model to infer the amount of accidents.

To have even a better understanding, we can see at how the MSE increases if a specific variable is not chosen, and how its node impurity increases. In this case, the more a variable is on the right, the more it is relevant for predicting the number of accidents.

plot_multi_way_importance(importance_frame, x_measure = "mse_increase", y_measure = "node_purity_increase", size_measure = "p_value", no_of_labels = 10)
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

This plot helps understanding which variables are crucial to minimize the error. According to it, Contro.veicoli.fermi, Intersezione and bici are relevant. Second to these we can also find Investimento.

Lets try to predict the accidents through this model on new/unseen data:

rf_preds <- predict(rf, newdata=new_df_test)

#RMSE
sqrt(sum((rf_preds - new_df_test$y)^2) / length(new_df_test$y))
## [1] 88.27707

With respect to the pruned tree, we are getting even better results (RMSE\(=88\) vs.\(100\)). Lets try to inspect the model through SHapely Additive exPlanations (SHAP). SHAP is a visualization tool that helps explaining black-box models allowing to compute the contribution of each feature to the predictions outputted by the model.

par(mfrow=c(1, 3))

y_train <- new_df_train$y
X_train <- subset(new_df_train, select=-c(y))
y_test <- new_df_test$y
X_test <- subset(new_df_test, select=-c(y))

exp_rf <- DALEX::explain(model=rf,
                         data=X_train,
                         y=y_train)

par(mfrow=c(1, 1))

By splitting the data into low, medium and high number of accidents per area and looking at the shap for each of them, we can try to understand in which direction each variable pushes to and what is its impact in the prediction:

  • low: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([0, 40]\). Here all the variables are pushing down the predictions, among the most important ones we can find Contro.veicoli.fermi and Intersezione. The value at which they pushes to lower number of accidents is zero, which means that when there are no accidents of type Contro.veicoli.fermi and no accidents in road segments Intersezione then the number of accidents overall decreases.

  • mid: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([41, 81]\). Coherently to what has been said in the previous scenario, we can see that a bit higher proportions of Contro.veicoli.fermi increases the number of accidents. After that, bici is another relevant variable, an increase in its proportions is associated to a general increase in the number of accidents, the same could be said for Intersezione.

  • high: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([82, 122]\). Here an increase in the proportions of Contro.veicoli.fermi, Intersezione and bici, as it was before, increases the overall number of predicted accidents. In this scenario, though, plays a role also the variable Investimento, of which proportions around \(0.12\) bring to an increase of the overall number of estimated accidents.

In general, it seems that the model relies on different values for pretty much the same variables while inferring the number of accidents. Of course the model cannot pre-determine in which scenario it is, but splitting the data this way allow to get a better idea about the exact proportions and their relevance.

By splitting the data into low, medium and high number of accidents per area and looking at the shap for each of them, we can try to understand in which direction each variable pushes to and what is its impact in the prediction:

  • low: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([0, 40]\). When the proportions of Provinciale and Traffico.Intenso are equal to zero, they are contributing negatively to the estimated number of accidents. When auto is zero, instead, the prediction of accidents is predicted as higher. Probably this is because the complete absence of accident that involved cars does not imply the complete absence of accidents. As I would expect, it is also possible to see that a proportion of Traffico.Scarso equal to zero contributes positively to the predicted number of accidents.

  • mid: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([41, 81]\). Here Provinciale and Viscido, when zero, are contributing negatively to the estimate of the accidents. While Bici and Incrocio with their respective values \(0.25\) and \(0.62\) contribute positively to the estimates. Again, Traffico.Intenso, when at \(0.06\) (still low) is contributing negatively to the predictions.

  • high: In this scenario, the number of accidents is in the range \([82, 122]\). Here, Viscido seems to positively contribute to the predictions with values around \(0.02\). After that, also Traffico.Intenso (when \(=0.21\)), Investimento (when \(=0.12\)) and bici (when $=034$) have a positive contribution to the predictions.

Summing up, the best models (in terms of prediction), among the trained ones, are SVM and Random Forest.

The models trained are not intended to be used for accident predictions in real scenarios though, not because they are performing poorly, but because, according to the nature of the data and its transformation, all the information required would be post-hoc (i.e., relative frequencies about the road segments involved, the type of accidents, ).

Some of the obtained results are still difficult to fully understand, despite the tools I have deployed to try understanding more the black-box models.

Nonetheless, implementing such models, capable of predicting the number of accidents in different areas of the city, is relevant to understand what variables are boosting (or lowering) the number of accidents.

As further improvements and possibilities to the current analyses, the data could be restructured in different ways and further enriched. In that case, it would be possible to implement other kind of models, that by including temporal and spatial information, for example could allow to effectively predict time and areas of future accidents. At this regard, the state of the art model is a conv-lstm, that showed pretty good capabilities in doing so.
